        <link id="build-style-article" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="/products/rsna/releasedAssets/css/build-article-8932601a697666afa607.css"/><article xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" data-design="pill" data-has="right-rail" data-type="research-article" vocab="http://schema.org/" typeof="ScholarlyArticle" lang="en" dir="ltr"><header data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><div data-article-access="no" data-article-access-type="other" class="meta-panel"><div class="meta-panel__left-content"><div class="meta-panel__label"><span>Cardiac Imaging</span></div><div class="meta-panel__onlineDate">Mar 12 2015</div></div><div class="meta-panel__right-content"><div class="meta-panel__share"></div></div></div><h1 property="name">Building a Bridge to Save a Failing Ventricle: Radiologic Evaluation of Short- and Long-term Cardiac Assist Devices</h1><div class="contributors"><span class="authors"><span class="heading">Authors</span>: <span role="list"><span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con1"><span property="givenName">Inas</span> <span property="familyName">Mohamed</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con2"><span property="givenName">Charles T.</span> <span property="familyName">Lau</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con3"><span property="givenName">Michael A.</span> <span property="familyName">Bolen</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con4"><span property="givenName">Ahmed H.</span> <span property="familyName">El-Sherief</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con5"><span property="givenName">Joseph T.</span> <span property="familyName">Azok</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con6"><span property="givenName">Jamshid H.</span> <span property="familyName">Karimov</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con7"><span property="givenName">Nader</span> <span property="familyName">Moazami</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, and <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con8"><span property="givenName">Rahul D.</span> <span property="familyName">Renapurkar</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a> <a href="/cdn-cgi/l/email-protection#94e6f1faf5e4e1e6d4f7f7f2bafbe6f3" property="email" aria-label="Email address"><span class="__cf_email__" data-cfemail="88faede6e9f8fdfac8ebebeea6e7faef">[email&#160;protected]</span></a></span></span></span><a href="#tab-contributors" class="to-authors-affiliations" data-id="article-authors-viewall">Authors Info &amp; Affiliations</a></div><div class="core-self-citation"><div property="isPartOf" typeof="Periodical"><span class="heading">Publication</span>: <span property="name">RadioGraphics</span></div><div class="core-enumeration"><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationVolume">Volume <span property="volumeNumber">35</span></span><span class="delimiter">, </span><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationIssue">Number <span property="issueNumber">2</span></span></div><div class="doi"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.352140149" property="sameAs">https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.352140149</a></div></div><div class="info-panel"><div class="info-panel__left-content"><div class="info-panel__metrics info-panel__item"></div></div><div class="info-panel__right-content"><div class="info-panel__article_tools info-panel__item">



        
        <div class="article-tools"><a href="/personalize/addFavoritePublication?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149" target="_blank" class="article-tools__favorite btn btn--slim btn--inverse" data-toggle="tooltip" data-trigger="hover" data-original-title="Add to favorites"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-add-favorite"></i><span class="sr-only">Add to favorites</span></a><a href="/action/addCitationAlert?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149" target="_blank" class="article-tools__citation btn btn--slim btn--inverse" data-toggle="tooltip" data-trigger="hover" data-original-title="Track Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-alert-bell"></i><span class="sr-only">Track Citations</span></a></div>
</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Heart failure is recognized with increasing frequency worldwide and often progresses to an advanced refractory state. Although the reference standard for treatment of advanced heart failure remains cardiac transplantation, the increasing shortage of donor organs and the unsuitability of many patients for transplantation surgery has led to a search for alternative therapies. One such therapy is mechanical circulatory support, which helps relieve the load on the ventricle and thereby allows it to recover function. In addition, there is increasing evidence supporting the use of mechanical devices as a bridge to recovery in patients with acute refractory heart failure. In this article, the imaging evaluation of various commonly used short- and long-term cardiac assist devices is discussed, and their relevant mechanisms of action and physiology are described. Imaging, particularly computed tomography (CT), plays a crucial role in preoperative evaluation for assessment of candidacy for implantation of a left ventricular assist device (LVAD) or total artificial heart (TAH). Also, echocardiography and CT are indispensable in assessment of complications associated with cardiac devices. Complications commonly associated with short-term assist devices include bleeding and malpositioning, whereas long-term devices such as LVADs may be associated with infection, pump thrombosis, and cannula malfunction, as well as bleeding. CT is also commonly performed for preoperative planning before LVAD or TAH explantation, replacement of a device or one of its components, and cardiac transplantation. <i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2015</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.352140149">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.352140149">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig1a.jpeg" height="784" width="652" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Schematic of an <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> device. <b>(a)</b> The <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> system consists of a balloon mounted on a flexible catheter inserted into the common femoral artery. <b>(b)</b> The <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> functions as a counterpulsation device: The balloon deflates during systole (left) to decrease afterload and inflates during diastole (right) to increase diastolic pressure and improve coronary flow. (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig1b.jpeg" height="784" width="673" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Schematic of an <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> device. <b>(a)</b> The <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> system consists of a balloon mounted on a flexible catheter inserted into the common femoral artery. <b>(b)</b> The <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> functions as a counterpulsation device: The balloon deflates during systole (left) to decrease afterload and inflates during diastole (right) to increase diastolic pressure and improve coronary flow. (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig2a.jpeg" height="665" width="791" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> Normal positioning of an <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> in a 57-year-old man with acute cardiogenic shock after acute myocardial infarction. <b>(a)</b> Anteroposterior (<abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr>) radiograph shows the radiopaque tip of the <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> 2–3 cm above the carina (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> unenhanced computed tomographic (CT) images show the inflated balloon in the descending thoracic aorta (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig2b.jpeg" height="665" width="884" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> Normal positioning of an <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> in a 57-year-old man with acute cardiogenic shock after acute myocardial infarction. <b>(a)</b> Anteroposterior (<abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr>) radiograph shows the radiopaque tip of the <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> 2–3 cm above the carina (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> unenhanced computed tomographic (CT) images show the inflated balloon in the descending thoracic aorta (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig2c.jpeg" height="643" width="849" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span> Normal positioning of an <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> in a 57-year-old man with acute cardiogenic shock after acute myocardial infarction. <b>(a)</b> Anteroposterior (<abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr>) radiograph shows the radiopaque tip of the <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> 2–3 cm above the carina (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> unenhanced computed tomographic (CT) images show the inflated balloon in the descending thoracic aorta (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig3a.jpeg" height="708" width="851" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Malpositioned <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> in a 58-year-old man with ischemic cardiomyopathy. <b>(a)</b> <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph shows the radiopaque tip of the <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> (arrowhead) below the carina (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial unenhanced chest CT image <b>(b)</b> and coronal unenhanced abdominal CT image <b>(c)</b> show the tip of the <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> in the distal descending thoracic aorta (arrow in <b>b</b>) and the balloon inflated in the abdominal aorta (arrow in <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig3b.jpeg" height="753" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Malpositioned <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> in a 58-year-old man with ischemic cardiomyopathy. <b>(a)</b> <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph shows the radiopaque tip of the <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> (arrowhead) below the carina (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial unenhanced chest CT image <b>(b)</b> and coronal unenhanced abdominal CT image <b>(c)</b> show the tip of the <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> in the distal descending thoracic aorta (arrow in <b>b</b>) and the balloon inflated in the abdominal aorta (arrow in <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig3c.jpeg" height="753" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span> Malpositioned <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> in a 58-year-old man with ischemic cardiomyopathy. <b>(a)</b> <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph shows the radiopaque tip of the <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> (arrowhead) below the carina (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial unenhanced chest CT image <b>(b)</b> and coronal unenhanced abdominal CT image <b>(c)</b> show the tip of the <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> in the distal descending thoracic aorta (arrow in <b>b</b>) and the balloon inflated in the abdominal aorta (arrow in <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig4a.jpeg" height="828" width="669" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Aortic dissection after <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> removal in a 24-year-old woman with peripartum cardiomyopathy. <b>(a)</b> Initial <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph shows the radiopaque tip of the <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> overlying the proximal descending thoracic aorta (arrow). After removal of the <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr>, the patient developed chest pain and right ventricular failure, for which contrast material–enhanced CT was performed with a pulmonary embolism protocol. <b>(b)</b> Coronal reformatted CT image shows a curvilinear dissection flap extending from the mid descending thoracic aorta to the proximal abdominal aorta (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig4b.jpeg" height="827" width="658" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Aortic dissection after <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> removal in a 24-year-old woman with peripartum cardiomyopathy. <b>(a)</b> Initial <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph shows the radiopaque tip of the <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr> overlying the proximal descending thoracic aorta (arrow). After removal of the <abbr title="intra-aortic balloon pump">IABP</abbr>, the patient developed chest pain and right ventricular failure, for which contrast material–enhanced CT was performed with a pulmonary embolism protocol. <b>(b)</b> Coronal reformatted CT image shows a curvilinear dissection flap extending from the mid descending thoracic aorta to the proximal abdominal aorta (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig5a.jpeg" height="562" width="632" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> <b>(a)</b> Diagram of venovenous <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> cannulation technique shows the infusion cannula placed in the superior vena cava (<abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr>) through a right internal jugular vein access and the drainage cannula placed near the junction of the right atrium and inferior vena cava (<abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr>) through a right femoral vein access. <b>(b–d)</b> Venovenous <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> in a 55-year-old man for treatment of acute respiratory distress syndrome after aortic valve replacement. <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph <b>(b)</b> and coronal unenhanced chest <b>(c)</b> and abdominal <b>(d)</b> CT images show the infusion cannula placed through the right internal jugular vein with the tip in the mid <abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr> (arrowhead) and the drainage cannula placed through the right femoral vein with the tip in the upper <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (arrow). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig5b.jpeg" height="922" width="659" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> <b>(a)</b> Diagram of venovenous <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> cannulation technique shows the infusion cannula placed in the superior vena cava (<abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr>) through a right internal jugular vein access and the drainage cannula placed near the junction of the right atrium and inferior vena cava (<abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr>) through a right femoral vein access. <b>(b–d)</b> Venovenous <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> in a 55-year-old man for treatment of acute respiratory distress syndrome after aortic valve replacement. <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph <b>(b)</b> and coronal unenhanced chest <b>(c)</b> and abdominal <b>(d)</b> CT images show the infusion cannula placed through the right internal jugular vein with the tip in the mid <abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr> (arrowhead) and the drainage cannula placed through the right femoral vein with the tip in the upper <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (arrow). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig5c.jpeg" height="562" width="693" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span> <b>(a)</b> Diagram of venovenous <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> cannulation technique shows the infusion cannula placed in the superior vena cava (<abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr>) through a right internal jugular vein access and the drainage cannula placed near the junction of the right atrium and inferior vena cava (<abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr>) through a right femoral vein access. <b>(b–d)</b> Venovenous <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> in a 55-year-old man for treatment of acute respiratory distress syndrome after aortic valve replacement. <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph <b>(b)</b> and coronal unenhanced chest <b>(c)</b> and abdominal <b>(d)</b> CT images show the infusion cannula placed through the right internal jugular vein with the tip in the mid <abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr> (arrowhead) and the drainage cannula placed through the right femoral vein with the tip in the upper <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (arrow). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig5d.jpeg" height="922" width="667" aria-labelledby="fig5d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5d</span> <b>(a)</b> Diagram of venovenous <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> cannulation technique shows the infusion cannula placed in the superior vena cava (<abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr>) through a right internal jugular vein access and the drainage cannula placed near the junction of the right atrium and inferior vena cava (<abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr>) through a right femoral vein access. <b>(b–d)</b> Venovenous <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> in a 55-year-old man for treatment of acute respiratory distress syndrome after aortic valve replacement. <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph <b>(b)</b> and coronal unenhanced chest <b>(c)</b> and abdominal <b>(d)</b> CT images show the infusion cannula placed through the right internal jugular vein with the tip in the mid <abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr> (arrowhead) and the drainage cannula placed through the right femoral vein with the tip in the upper <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (arrow). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig5d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig6a.jpeg" height="1094" width="196" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Avalon Elite double-lumen venovenous <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr>. <b>(a–c)</b> Photographs <b>(a, b)</b> and diagram <b>(c)</b> show the double-lumen cannula, which is placed through the right internal jugular vein into the right atrium, with its tip in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr>. Deoxygenated blood in the <abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr> and <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> enters one lumen through an outer fenestrated venous catheter wall (arrows in <b>b</b>), and a second lumen allows oxygenated blood to be returned from the external pump to the mid right atrium via an opening (arrowhead in <b>b</b>) directed toward the tricuspid valve. <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph obtained in a 60-year-old man with acute respiratory distress syndrome shows the normal appearance of Avalon Elite double-lumen venovenous <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> therapy (arrow). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig6b.jpeg" height="1094" width="220" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Avalon Elite double-lumen venovenous <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr>. <b>(a–c)</b> Photographs <b>(a, b)</b> and diagram <b>(c)</b> show the double-lumen cannula, which is placed through the right internal jugular vein into the right atrium, with its tip in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr>. Deoxygenated blood in the <abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr> and <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> enters one lumen through an outer fenestrated venous catheter wall (arrows in <b>b</b>), and a second lumen allows oxygenated blood to be returned from the external pump to the mid right atrium via an opening (arrowhead in <b>b</b>) directed toward the tricuspid valve. <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph obtained in a 60-year-old man with acute respiratory distress syndrome shows the normal appearance of Avalon Elite double-lumen venovenous <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> therapy (arrow). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig6c.jpeg" height="1094" width="635" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span> Avalon Elite double-lumen venovenous <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr>. <b>(a–c)</b> Photographs <b>(a, b)</b> and diagram <b>(c)</b> show the double-lumen cannula, which is placed through the right internal jugular vein into the right atrium, with its tip in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr>. Deoxygenated blood in the <abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr> and <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> enters one lumen through an outer fenestrated venous catheter wall (arrows in <b>b</b>), and a second lumen allows oxygenated blood to be returned from the external pump to the mid right atrium via an opening (arrowhead in <b>b</b>) directed toward the tricuspid valve. <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph obtained in a 60-year-old man with acute respiratory distress syndrome shows the normal appearance of Avalon Elite double-lumen venovenous <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> therapy (arrow). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig6d.jpeg" height="1094" width="779" aria-labelledby="fig6d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6d</span> Avalon Elite double-lumen venovenous <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr>. <b>(a–c)</b> Photographs <b>(a, b)</b> and diagram <b>(c)</b> show the double-lumen cannula, which is placed through the right internal jugular vein into the right atrium, with its tip in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr>. Deoxygenated blood in the <abbr title="superior vena cava">SVC</abbr> and <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> enters one lumen through an outer fenestrated venous catheter wall (arrows in <b>b</b>), and a second lumen allows oxygenated blood to be returned from the external pump to the mid right atrium via an opening (arrowhead in <b>b</b>) directed toward the tricuspid valve. <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph obtained in a 60-year-old man with acute respiratory distress syndrome shows the normal appearance of Avalon Elite double-lumen venovenous <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> therapy (arrow). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig6d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig7a.jpeg" height="692" width="749" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> cannulation sites. <b>(a–c)</b> Diagrams show various possible sites of venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> cannulation. In <b>a</b>, a venous cannula is placed in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> through a femoral vein access, and an arterial catheter is placed in the femoral artery (most common). In <b>b</b>, a venous cannula is placed in the right atrium, and an arterial catheter is placed in the ascending aorta (central <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr>). In <b>c</b>, a venous cannula is placed in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> through a femoral vein access, and an arterial catheter is placed in the ascending aorta. <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph shows venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> therapy for treatment of respiratory failure and cardiogenic shock after aortic valve repair in a 72-year-old woman. The arterial cannula is anastomosed to the right axillary artery (white arrow) and the venous catheter is anastomosed to the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow). <b>(e)</b> Radiograph from a study of the kidneys, ureter, and bladder shows a venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> system inserted percutaneously for treatment of postischemic acute cardiogenic shock in a 59-year-old man. The arterial cannula is seen in the left femoral artery (black arrowhead), and the venous cannula is seen in the left femoral vein (white arrowhead). A distal posterior tibial artery retrograde perfusion catheter is also present (arrow). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig7b.jpeg" height="447" width="299" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> cannulation sites. <b>(a–c)</b> Diagrams show various possible sites of venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> cannulation. In <b>a</b>, a venous cannula is placed in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> through a femoral vein access, and an arterial catheter is placed in the femoral artery (most common). In <b>b</b>, a venous cannula is placed in the right atrium, and an arterial catheter is placed in the ascending aorta (central <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr>). In <b>c</b>, a venous cannula is placed in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> through a femoral vein access, and an arterial catheter is placed in the ascending aorta. <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph shows venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> therapy for treatment of respiratory failure and cardiogenic shock after aortic valve repair in a 72-year-old woman. The arterial cannula is anastomosed to the right axillary artery (white arrow) and the venous catheter is anastomosed to the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow). <b>(e)</b> Radiograph from a study of the kidneys, ureter, and bladder shows a venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> system inserted percutaneously for treatment of postischemic acute cardiogenic shock in a 59-year-old man. The arterial cannula is seen in the left femoral artery (black arrowhead), and the venous cannula is seen in the left femoral vein (white arrowhead). A distal posterior tibial artery retrograde perfusion catheter is also present (arrow). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig7c.jpeg" height="420" width="299" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span> Venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> cannulation sites. <b>(a–c)</b> Diagrams show various possible sites of venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> cannulation. In <b>a</b>, a venous cannula is placed in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> through a femoral vein access, and an arterial catheter is placed in the femoral artery (most common). In <b>b</b>, a venous cannula is placed in the right atrium, and an arterial catheter is placed in the ascending aorta (central <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr>). In <b>c</b>, a venous cannula is placed in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> through a femoral vein access, and an arterial catheter is placed in the ascending aorta. <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph shows venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> therapy for treatment of respiratory failure and cardiogenic shock after aortic valve repair in a 72-year-old woman. The arterial cannula is anastomosed to the right axillary artery (white arrow) and the venous catheter is anastomosed to the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow). <b>(e)</b> Radiograph from a study of the kidneys, ureter, and bladder shows a venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> system inserted percutaneously for treatment of postischemic acute cardiogenic shock in a 59-year-old man. The arterial cannula is seen in the left femoral artery (black arrowhead), and the venous cannula is seen in the left femoral vein (white arrowhead). A distal posterior tibial artery retrograde perfusion catheter is also present (arrow). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig7d.jpeg" height="939" width="658" aria-labelledby="fig7d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span> Venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> cannulation sites. <b>(a–c)</b> Diagrams show various possible sites of venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> cannulation. In <b>a</b>, a venous cannula is placed in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> through a femoral vein access, and an arterial catheter is placed in the femoral artery (most common). In <b>b</b>, a venous cannula is placed in the right atrium, and an arterial catheter is placed in the ascending aorta (central <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr>). In <b>c</b>, a venous cannula is placed in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> through a femoral vein access, and an arterial catheter is placed in the ascending aorta. <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph shows venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> therapy for treatment of respiratory failure and cardiogenic shock after aortic valve repair in a 72-year-old woman. The arterial cannula is anastomosed to the right axillary artery (white arrow) and the venous catheter is anastomosed to the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow). <b>(e)</b> Radiograph from a study of the kidneys, ureter, and bladder shows a venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> system inserted percutaneously for treatment of postischemic acute cardiogenic shock in a 59-year-old man. The arterial cannula is seen in the left femoral artery (black arrowhead), and the venous cannula is seen in the left femoral vein (white arrowhead). A distal posterior tibial artery retrograde perfusion catheter is also present (arrow). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig7d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig7e.jpeg" height="939" width="695" aria-labelledby="fig7e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7e</span> Venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> cannulation sites. <b>(a–c)</b> Diagrams show various possible sites of venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> cannulation. In <b>a</b>, a venous cannula is placed in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> through a femoral vein access, and an arterial catheter is placed in the femoral artery (most common). In <b>b</b>, a venous cannula is placed in the right atrium, and an arterial catheter is placed in the ascending aorta (central <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr>). In <b>c</b>, a venous cannula is placed in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> through a femoral vein access, and an arterial catheter is placed in the ascending aorta. <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph shows venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> therapy for treatment of respiratory failure and cardiogenic shock after aortic valve repair in a 72-year-old woman. The arterial cannula is anastomosed to the right axillary artery (white arrow) and the venous catheter is anastomosed to the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow). <b>(e)</b> Radiograph from a study of the kidneys, ureter, and bladder shows a venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> system inserted percutaneously for treatment of postischemic acute cardiogenic shock in a 59-year-old man. The arterial cannula is seen in the left femoral artery (black arrowhead), and the venous cannula is seen in the left femoral vein (white arrowhead). A distal posterior tibial artery retrograde perfusion catheter is also present (arrow). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig7e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig8a.jpeg" height="702" width="853" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr>-related thromboembolic events in two patients. <b>(a)</b> CT with a pulmonary embolism protocol was performed in a 46-year-old man with shortness of breath and tachycardia after placement of a central venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> system and an <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> (HeartMate II) for treatment of ischemic cardiomyopathy. Axial chest CT image shows a filling defect in the right main pulmonary artery (black arrow), a finding indicative of pulmonary embolism. The anastomosis of the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> outflow graft to the ascending aorta (white arrow) appears intact. <b>(b)</b> Unenhanced CT of the brain was performed in a 48-year-old man with episodic slurred speech after venovenous <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> therapy for respiratory failure occurring as a complication of right lung transplant for interstitial pulmonary fibrosis. Axial CT image reveals an area of hypoattenuation (arrow) suggestive of infarction in the left occipital region.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig8b.jpeg" height="702" width="622" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr>-related thromboembolic events in two patients. <b>(a)</b> CT with a pulmonary embolism protocol was performed in a 46-year-old man with shortness of breath and tachycardia after placement of a central venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> system and an <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> (HeartMate II) for treatment of ischemic cardiomyopathy. Axial chest CT image shows a filling defect in the right main pulmonary artery (black arrow), a finding indicative of pulmonary embolism. The anastomosis of the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> outflow graft to the ascending aorta (white arrow) appears intact. <b>(b)</b> Unenhanced CT of the brain was performed in a 48-year-old man with episodic slurred speech after venovenous <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> therapy for respiratory failure occurring as a complication of right lung transplant for interstitial pulmonary fibrosis. Axial CT image reveals an area of hypoattenuation (arrow) suggestive of infarction in the left occipital region.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig9a.jpeg" height="449" width="747" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr>–related arterial thrombosis in a 21-year-old woman who underwent placement of a peripheral left femoral vein–femoral artery venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> after a heart transplant complicated by rejection and acute cardiogenic shock. CT angiography with femoral runoff was performed for left foot ischemia. Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and volume-rendering technique (<abbr title="volume-rendering technique">VRT</abbr>) <b>(c)</b> images reveal complete occlusion of the left external iliac and common femoral arteries (straight white arrow) with distal reconstitution of the superficial femoral and profunda femoris arteries (curved white arrow). Of note, the right common femoral artery is well opacified (black arrows). A left groin surgical drain is visible on the axial and coronal images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig9b.jpeg" height="440" width="747" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr>–related arterial thrombosis in a 21-year-old woman who underwent placement of a peripheral left femoral vein–femoral artery venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> after a heart transplant complicated by rejection and acute cardiogenic shock. CT angiography with femoral runoff was performed for left foot ischemia. Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and volume-rendering technique (<abbr title="volume-rendering technique">VRT</abbr>) <b>(c)</b> images reveal complete occlusion of the left external iliac and common femoral arteries (straight white arrow) with distal reconstitution of the superficial femoral and profunda femoris arteries (curved white arrow). Of note, the right common femoral artery is well opacified (black arrows). A left groin surgical drain is visible on the axial and coronal images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig9c.jpeg" height="960" width="732" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span> Venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr>–related arterial thrombosis in a 21-year-old woman who underwent placement of a peripheral left femoral vein–femoral artery venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> after a heart transplant complicated by rejection and acute cardiogenic shock. CT angiography with femoral runoff was performed for left foot ischemia. Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and volume-rendering technique (<abbr title="volume-rendering technique">VRT</abbr>) <b>(c)</b> images reveal complete occlusion of the left external iliac and common femoral arteries (straight white arrow) with distal reconstitution of the superficial femoral and profunda femoris arteries (curved white arrow). Of note, the right common femoral artery is well opacified (black arrows). A left groin surgical drain is visible on the axial and coronal images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig10.jpeg" height="806" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span> <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr>-related pneumothorax in a 21-year-old woman who underwent venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> therapy for severe pulmonary hypertension and peripartum cardiogenic shock. <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph obtained immediately after <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> system placement reveals a deep sulcus sign representing a large right pneumothorax (white arrow). The venous <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> cannula is seen coursing through the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig11a.jpeg" height="651" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Cardiac stasis and unusual blood opacification at chest CT in a 68-year-old woman who underwent placement of a femoral vein and femoral artery venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> system for pulseless electrical activity after coronary artery bypass graft surgery. Chest CT with a pulmonary embolism protocol was performed with iodinated contrast material injected through a pulmonary arterial catheter while the patient was on full venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> support. Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(c)</b> CT images show opacification of the right cardiac chambers because of contrast material–containing blood from the pulmonary artery and retrograde opacification of the descending thoracic aorta because of opacified blood returning via the femoral arterial cannula (black arrow). The ascending thoracic aorta (white arrow) and left cardiac chambers are nonopacified. The left cardiac chambers are essentially bypassed, which leads to blood stasis and thrombus formation. Swirling contrast material in the lumen of the ascending aorta produces flow artifact (arrowhead), mimicking a dissection flap.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig11b.jpeg" height="651" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Cardiac stasis and unusual blood opacification at chest CT in a 68-year-old woman who underwent placement of a femoral vein and femoral artery venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> system for pulseless electrical activity after coronary artery bypass graft surgery. Chest CT with a pulmonary embolism protocol was performed with iodinated contrast material injected through a pulmonary arterial catheter while the patient was on full venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> support. Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(c)</b> CT images show opacification of the right cardiac chambers because of contrast material–containing blood from the pulmonary artery and retrograde opacification of the descending thoracic aorta because of opacified blood returning via the femoral arterial cannula (black arrow). The ascending thoracic aorta (white arrow) and left cardiac chambers are nonopacified. The left cardiac chambers are essentially bypassed, which leads to blood stasis and thrombus formation. Swirling contrast material in the lumen of the ascending aorta produces flow artifact (arrowhead), mimicking a dissection flap.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig11c.jpeg" height="823" width="600" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span> Cardiac stasis and unusual blood opacification at chest CT in a 68-year-old woman who underwent placement of a femoral vein and femoral artery venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> system for pulseless electrical activity after coronary artery bypass graft surgery. Chest CT with a pulmonary embolism protocol was performed with iodinated contrast material injected through a pulmonary arterial catheter while the patient was on full venoarterial <abbr title="extracorporeal membrane oxygenation">ECMO</abbr> support. Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(c)</b> CT images show opacification of the right cardiac chambers because of contrast material–containing blood from the pulmonary artery and retrograde opacification of the descending thoracic aorta because of opacified blood returning via the femoral arterial cannula (black arrow). The ascending thoracic aorta (white arrow) and left cardiac chambers are nonopacified. The left cardiac chambers are essentially bypassed, which leads to blood stasis and thrombus formation. Swirling contrast material in the lumen of the ascending aorta produces flow artifact (arrowhead), mimicking a dissection flap.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig12a.jpeg" height="396" width="617" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Impella device. <b>(a–c)</b> Photographs <b>(a, b)</b> and diagram <b>(c)</b> show the Impella 2.5 device, which draws blood from the left ventricle through an inlet area (black arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) near the distal tip and expels blood into the ascending aorta through an outlet area (white arrow in <b>a</b>). The device is inserted through the femoral artery into the ascending aorta and placed across the valve with its distal tip coiled in the left ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Posteroanterior chest radiograph shows normal positioning of an Impella 2.5 device (arrow) in a 61-year-old man with myocarditis complicated by ventricular fibrillation arrest. (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig12b.jpeg" height="395" width="617" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Impella device. <b>(a–c)</b> Photographs <b>(a, b)</b> and diagram <b>(c)</b> show the Impella 2.5 device, which draws blood from the left ventricle through an inlet area (black arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) near the distal tip and expels blood into the ascending aorta through an outlet area (white arrow in <b>a</b>). The device is inserted through the femoral artery into the ascending aorta and placed across the valve with its distal tip coiled in the left ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Posteroanterior chest radiograph shows normal positioning of an Impella 2.5 device (arrow) in a 61-year-old man with myocarditis complicated by ventricular fibrillation arrest. (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig12c.jpeg" height="865" width="564" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span> Impella device. <b>(a–c)</b> Photographs <b>(a, b)</b> and diagram <b>(c)</b> show the Impella 2.5 device, which draws blood from the left ventricle through an inlet area (black arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) near the distal tip and expels blood into the ascending aorta through an outlet area (white arrow in <b>a</b>). The device is inserted through the femoral artery into the ascending aorta and placed across the valve with its distal tip coiled in the left ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Posteroanterior chest radiograph shows normal positioning of an Impella 2.5 device (arrow) in a 61-year-old man with myocarditis complicated by ventricular fibrillation arrest. (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig12d.jpeg" height="865" width="671" aria-labelledby="fig12d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12d</span> Impella device. <b>(a–c)</b> Photographs <b>(a, b)</b> and diagram <b>(c)</b> show the Impella 2.5 device, which draws blood from the left ventricle through an inlet area (black arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) near the distal tip and expels blood into the ascending aorta through an outlet area (white arrow in <b>a</b>). The device is inserted through the femoral artery into the ascending aorta and placed across the valve with its distal tip coiled in the left ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Posteroanterior chest radiograph shows normal positioning of an Impella 2.5 device (arrow) in a 61-year-old man with myocarditis complicated by ventricular fibrillation arrest. (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig12d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig13a.jpeg" height="344" width="413" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> TandemHeart. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows the TandemHeart pump. <b>(b)</b> Diagram of the device shows introduction of the venous inflow catheter (placed via the femoral vein; not shown) into the left atrium by means of trans–atrial septal perforation. <b>(c, d)</b> TandemHeart implanted in the right femoral artery and vein for treatment of restrictive cardiomyopathy and pulmonary hypertension in a 46-year-old man before heart and lung transplantation. <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph shows the transseptal venous cannula with its proximal end projecting over the left atrium (arrow in <b>c</b>). Abdominal radiograph shows the venous cannula within the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (arrow in <b>d</b>). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig13b.jpeg" height="563" width="413" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> TandemHeart. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows the TandemHeart pump. <b>(b)</b> Diagram of the device shows introduction of the venous inflow catheter (placed via the femoral vein; not shown) into the left atrium by means of trans–atrial septal perforation. <b>(c, d)</b> TandemHeart implanted in the right femoral artery and vein for treatment of restrictive cardiomyopathy and pulmonary hypertension in a 46-year-old man before heart and lung transplantation. <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph shows the transseptal venous cannula with its proximal end projecting over the left atrium (arrow in <b>c</b>). Abdominal radiograph shows the venous cannula within the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (arrow in <b>d</b>). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig13c.jpeg" height="981" width="602" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span> TandemHeart. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows the TandemHeart pump. <b>(b)</b> Diagram of the device shows introduction of the venous inflow catheter (placed via the femoral vein; not shown) into the left atrium by means of trans–atrial septal perforation. <b>(c, d)</b> TandemHeart implanted in the right femoral artery and vein for treatment of restrictive cardiomyopathy and pulmonary hypertension in a 46-year-old man before heart and lung transplantation. <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph shows the transseptal venous cannula with its proximal end projecting over the left atrium (arrow in <b>c</b>). Abdominal radiograph shows the venous cannula within the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (arrow in <b>d</b>). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig13d.jpeg" height="981" width="635" aria-labelledby="fig13d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13d</span> TandemHeart. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows the TandemHeart pump. <b>(b)</b> Diagram of the device shows introduction of the venous inflow catheter (placed via the femoral vein; not shown) into the left atrium by means of trans–atrial septal perforation. <b>(c, d)</b> TandemHeart implanted in the right femoral artery and vein for treatment of restrictive cardiomyopathy and pulmonary hypertension in a 46-year-old man before heart and lung transplantation. <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph shows the transseptal venous cannula with its proximal end projecting over the left atrium (arrow in <b>c</b>). Abdominal radiograph shows the venous cannula within the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (arrow in <b>d</b>). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig13d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig14a.jpeg" height="400" width="345" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> Surgically inserted short-term VADs. <b>(a, b)</b> Photographs show the AB5000 <b>(a)</b> and CentriMag <b>(b)</b> pumps. <b>(c)</b> Diagram shows implantation of the BVS 5000 system for biventricular support, with the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> inflow cannula attached to the left atrium, the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> outflow graft anastomosed to the ascending aorta, the <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> inflow cannula attached to the right atrium, and the <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> outflow graft anastomosed to the pulmonary artery. <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph obtained in a 57-year-old man with a CentriMag <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> implant for treatment of right ventricular failure after heart transplantation shows the outflow cannula anastomosis to the pulmonary artery (white arrow) and the inflow cannula anastomosis to the right atrium (black arrow). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig14b.jpeg" height="315" width="345" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> Surgically inserted short-term VADs. <b>(a, b)</b> Photographs show the AB5000 <b>(a)</b> and CentriMag <b>(b)</b> pumps. <b>(c)</b> Diagram shows implantation of the BVS 5000 system for biventricular support, with the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> inflow cannula attached to the left atrium, the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> outflow graft anastomosed to the ascending aorta, the <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> inflow cannula attached to the right atrium, and the <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> outflow graft anastomosed to the pulmonary artery. <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph obtained in a 57-year-old man with a CentriMag <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> implant for treatment of right ventricular failure after heart transplantation shows the outflow cannula anastomosis to the pulmonary artery (white arrow) and the inflow cannula anastomosis to the right atrium (black arrow). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig14c.jpeg" height="789" width="700" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span> Surgically inserted short-term VADs. <b>(a, b)</b> Photographs show the AB5000 <b>(a)</b> and CentriMag <b>(b)</b> pumps. <b>(c)</b> Diagram shows implantation of the BVS 5000 system for biventricular support, with the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> inflow cannula attached to the left atrium, the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> outflow graft anastomosed to the ascending aorta, the <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> inflow cannula attached to the right atrium, and the <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> outflow graft anastomosed to the pulmonary artery. <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph obtained in a 57-year-old man with a CentriMag <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> implant for treatment of right ventricular failure after heart transplantation shows the outflow cannula anastomosis to the pulmonary artery (white arrow) and the inflow cannula anastomosis to the right atrium (black arrow). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig14d.jpeg" height="789" width="605" aria-labelledby="fig14d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14d</span> Surgically inserted short-term VADs. <b>(a, b)</b> Photographs show the AB5000 <b>(a)</b> and CentriMag <b>(b)</b> pumps. <b>(c)</b> Diagram shows implantation of the BVS 5000 system for biventricular support, with the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> inflow cannula attached to the left atrium, the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> outflow graft anastomosed to the ascending aorta, the <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> inflow cannula attached to the right atrium, and the <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> outflow graft anastomosed to the pulmonary artery. <b>(d)</b> <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph obtained in a 57-year-old man with a CentriMag <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> implant for treatment of right ventricular failure after heart transplantation shows the outflow cannula anastomosis to the pulmonary artery (white arrow) and the inflow cannula anastomosis to the right atrium (black arrow). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig14d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig15a.jpeg" height="861" width="328" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span> Thoratec PVAD. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows the PVAD pump. <b>(b)</b> Diagram shows implantation of the PVAD system for biventricular support, with the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> inflow cannula attached to the left atrium, the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> outflow graft anastomosed to the ascending aorta, the <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> inflow cannula attached to the right atrium, and the <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> outflow graft anastomosed to the pulmonary artery. <i>Lt</i> = left, <i>Rt</i> = right. <b>(c)</b> Scout image obtained in a 53-year-old man who underwent implantation of the device for treatment of acute myocardial infarction and acute cardiogenic shock with biventricular failure shows the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> inflow (black arrow), <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> outflow (black arrowhead), <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> inflow (white arrow), and <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> outflow (white arrowhead) cannulas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig15b.jpeg" height="859" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> Thoratec PVAD. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows the PVAD pump. <b>(b)</b> Diagram shows implantation of the PVAD system for biventricular support, with the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> inflow cannula attached to the left atrium, the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> outflow graft anastomosed to the ascending aorta, the <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> inflow cannula attached to the right atrium, and the <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> outflow graft anastomosed to the pulmonary artery. <i>Lt</i> = left, <i>Rt</i> = right. <b>(c)</b> Scout image obtained in a 53-year-old man who underwent implantation of the device for treatment of acute myocardial infarction and acute cardiogenic shock with biventricular failure shows the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> inflow (black arrow), <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> outflow (black arrowhead), <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> inflow (white arrow), and <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> outflow (white arrowhead) cannulas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig15c.jpeg" height="861" width="680" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span> Thoratec PVAD. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows the PVAD pump. <b>(b)</b> Diagram shows implantation of the PVAD system for biventricular support, with the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> inflow cannula attached to the left atrium, the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> outflow graft anastomosed to the ascending aorta, the <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> inflow cannula attached to the right atrium, and the <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> outflow graft anastomosed to the pulmonary artery. <i>Lt</i> = left, <i>Rt</i> = right. <b>(c)</b> Scout image obtained in a 53-year-old man who underwent implantation of the device for treatment of acute myocardial infarction and acute cardiogenic shock with biventricular failure shows the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> inflow (black arrow), <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> outflow (black arrowhead), <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> inflow (white arrow), and <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> outflow (white arrowhead) cannulas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig16a.jpeg" height="506" width="400" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> Novacor <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows the Novacor pump. <b>(b)</b> Diagram of the Novacor <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> system shows the inflow cannula attached to the left ventricle and the outflow graft anastomosed to the ascending aorta. <b>(c, d)</b> Scout <b>(c)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(d)</b> images from contrast-enhanced CT in a 22-year-old woman after Novacor <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> implantation as bridge-to-transplant therapy show the Novacor pump (straight black arrow) placed in the abdomen with the driveline overlying the abdomen (curved arrow in <b>c</b>). A portion of the outflow cannula is seen extending into the chest (white arrow in <b>d</b>). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig16b.jpeg" height="909" width="574" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> Novacor <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows the Novacor pump. <b>(b)</b> Diagram of the Novacor <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> system shows the inflow cannula attached to the left ventricle and the outflow graft anastomosed to the ascending aorta. <b>(c, d)</b> Scout <b>(c)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(d)</b> images from contrast-enhanced CT in a 22-year-old woman after Novacor <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> implantation as bridge-to-transplant therapy show the Novacor pump (straight black arrow) placed in the abdomen with the driveline overlying the abdomen (curved arrow in <b>c</b>). A portion of the outflow cannula is seen extending into the chest (white arrow in <b>d</b>). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig16c.jpeg" height="909" width="626" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span> Novacor <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows the Novacor pump. <b>(b)</b> Diagram of the Novacor <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> system shows the inflow cannula attached to the left ventricle and the outflow graft anastomosed to the ascending aorta. <b>(c, d)</b> Scout <b>(c)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(d)</b> images from contrast-enhanced CT in a 22-year-old woman after Novacor <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> implantation as bridge-to-transplant therapy show the Novacor pump (straight black arrow) placed in the abdomen with the driveline overlying the abdomen (curved arrow in <b>c</b>). A portion of the outflow cannula is seen extending into the chest (white arrow in <b>d</b>). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig16d.jpeg" height="909" width="650" aria-labelledby="fig16d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16d</span> Novacor <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows the Novacor pump. <b>(b)</b> Diagram of the Novacor <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> system shows the inflow cannula attached to the left ventricle and the outflow graft anastomosed to the ascending aorta. <b>(c, d)</b> Scout <b>(c)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(d)</b> images from contrast-enhanced CT in a 22-year-old woman after Novacor <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> implantation as bridge-to-transplant therapy show the Novacor pump (straight black arrow) placed in the abdomen with the driveline overlying the abdomen (curved arrow in <b>c</b>). A portion of the outflow cannula is seen extending into the chest (white arrow in <b>d</b>). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig16d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig17a.jpeg" height="562" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span> HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows the pump (straight black arrow), the inflow cannula (white arrowhead) including the flexible inflow conduit, the outflow cannula surrounded by the bend relief (straight white arrow) and attached to the pump with a snap ring (curved black arrow), the driveline (curved white arrow), and the device controller (black arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Diagrams show the HeartMate II system implanted as an <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>, with blood from the left ventricle passing through the inflow cannula (left) and pumped into the ascending aorta through the outflow graft (right). <b>(c)</b> Scout image in a 39-year-old man with ischemic cardiomyopathy who received a HeartMate II implant shows the pump (straight black arrow), the inflow cannula (white arrowhead), the outflow graft snap ring (curved black arrow), the driveline (white arrow), and the device controller (black arrowhead). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig17b.jpeg" height="604" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span> HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows the pump (straight black arrow), the inflow cannula (white arrowhead) including the flexible inflow conduit, the outflow cannula surrounded by the bend relief (straight white arrow) and attached to the pump with a snap ring (curved black arrow), the driveline (curved white arrow), and the device controller (black arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Diagrams show the HeartMate II system implanted as an <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>, with blood from the left ventricle passing through the inflow cannula (left) and pumped into the ascending aorta through the outflow graft (right). <b>(c)</b> Scout image in a 39-year-old man with ischemic cardiomyopathy who received a HeartMate II implant shows the pump (straight black arrow), the inflow cannula (white arrowhead), the outflow graft snap ring (curved black arrow), the driveline (white arrow), and the device controller (black arrowhead). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig17c.jpeg" height="1010" width="674" aria-labelledby="fig17c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17c</span> HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows the pump (straight black arrow), the inflow cannula (white arrowhead) including the flexible inflow conduit, the outflow cannula surrounded by the bend relief (straight white arrow) and attached to the pump with a snap ring (curved black arrow), the driveline (curved white arrow), and the device controller (black arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Diagrams show the HeartMate II system implanted as an <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>, with blood from the left ventricle passing through the inflow cannula (left) and pumped into the ascending aorta through the outflow graft (right). <b>(c)</b> Scout image in a 39-year-old man with ischemic cardiomyopathy who received a HeartMate II implant shows the pump (straight black arrow), the inflow cannula (white arrowhead), the outflow graft snap ring (curved black arrow), the driveline (white arrow), and the device controller (black arrowhead). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig17c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig18a.jpeg" height="791" width="855" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(b)</b> images from contrast-enhanced chest CT in a 39-year-old man with a HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> implant for refractory ischemic cardiomyopathy show the outflow graft, the inflow cannula (black arrow) attached to the left ventricle, and the pump (arrowhead). White arrow = Gore-Tex (polytetrafluoroethylene) graft covering the outflow graft. Circumferential low attenuation between the outflow graft and the outer Gore-Tex graft indicates the space between those two layers and should not be misinterpreted as thrombus or neointimal buildup.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig18b.jpeg" height="791" width="720" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(b)</b> images from contrast-enhanced chest CT in a 39-year-old man with a HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> implant for refractory ischemic cardiomyopathy show the outflow graft, the inflow cannula (black arrow) attached to the left ventricle, and the pump (arrowhead). White arrow = Gore-Tex (polytetrafluoroethylene) graft covering the outflow graft. Circumferential low attenuation between the outflow graft and the outer Gore-Tex graft indicates the space between those two layers and should not be misinterpreted as thrombus or neointimal buildup.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig19a.jpeg" height="653" width="556" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> Jarvik <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows the Jarvik <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> pump. <b>(b)</b> Diagram shows implantation of the Jarvik <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> system with a small pump positioned in the left ventricle and an outflow cannula anastomosed to the descending thoracic aorta. (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig19b.jpeg" height="653" width="567" aria-l