of the device with the pump attached to the left ventricle and the outflow graft anastomosed to the ascending aorta. <b>(e)</b> Scout image in a 65-year-old man after HVAD system implantation for refractory dilated cardiomyopathy shows the pump (black arrow) overlying the left ventricle and its driveline (white arrow). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig20e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig21a.jpeg" height="698" width="844" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span> HVAD implant used as a bridge to transplantation in a 65-year-old man with refractory dilated cardiomyopathy. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial images obtained with mediastinal <b>(a)</b> and lung <b>(b)</b> window settings show the HVAD pump (black arrow) attached to the left ventricle with the outflow graft (white arrow) anastomosed to the ascending aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig21b.jpeg" height="698" width="831" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span> HVAD implant used as a bridge to transplantation in a 65-year-old man with refractory dilated cardiomyopathy. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial images obtained with mediastinal <b>(a)</b> and lung <b>(b)</b> window settings show the HVAD pump (black arrow) attached to the left ventricle with the outflow graft (white arrow) anastomosed to the ascending aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig22a.jpeg" height="736" width="889" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span> <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>-related hematomas. <b>(a)</b> A 62-year-old man with refractory ischemic cardiomyopathy received a HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> as a bridge to transplant; he presented with tachycardia and shortness of breath. Axial unenhanced chest CT image shows a loculated high-attenuation fluid collection in the left anterior pleural space (arrow), indicative of hemothorax. <b>(b)</b> A 36-year-old woman with acute lymphocytic leukemia and chemotherapy-induced cardiomyopathy received a HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> as destination therapy; she presented with chest pain and tachycardia and was diagnosed with hypotension. Axial unenhanced chest CT image shows high-attenuation pericardial effusion (arrow), indicative of hemopericardium. <b>(c)</b> A 73-year-old man with refractory ischemic cardiomyopathy received a HeartMate II implant as destination therapy; he presented with left chest wall swelling and tenderness. Axial unenhanced chest CT image shows a large heterogeneous high-attenuating subcutaneous fluid collection (arrow), indicative of left chest wall hematoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig22b.jpeg" height="736" width="786" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span> <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>-related hematomas. <b>(a)</b> A 62-year-old man with refractory ischemic cardiomyopathy received a HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> as a bridge to transplant; he presented with tachycardia and shortness of breath. Axial unenhanced chest CT image shows a loculated high-attenuation fluid collection in the left anterior pleural space (arrow), indicative of hemothorax. <b>(b)</b> A 36-year-old woman with acute lymphocytic leukemia and chemotherapy-induced cardiomyopathy received a HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> as destination therapy; she presented with chest pain and tachycardia and was diagnosed with hypotension. Axial unenhanced chest CT image shows high-attenuation pericardial effusion (arrow), indicative of hemopericardium. <b>(c)</b> A 73-year-old man with refractory ischemic cardiomyopathy received a HeartMate II implant as destination therapy; he presented with left chest wall swelling and tenderness. Axial unenhanced chest CT image shows a large heterogeneous high-attenuating subcutaneous fluid collection (arrow), indicative of left chest wall hematoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig22c.jpeg" height="651" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig22c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22c</span> <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>-related hematomas. <b>(a)</b> A 62-year-old man with refractory ischemic cardiomyopathy received a HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> as a bridge to transplant; he presented with tachycardia and shortness of breath. Axial unenhanced chest CT image shows a loculated high-attenuation fluid collection in the left anterior pleural space (arrow), indicative of hemothorax. <b>(b)</b> A 36-year-old woman with acute lymphocytic leukemia and chemotherapy-induced cardiomyopathy received a HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> as destination therapy; she presented with chest pain and tachycardia and was diagnosed with hypotension. Axial unenhanced chest CT image shows high-attenuation pericardial effusion (arrow), indicative of hemopericardium. <b>(c)</b> A 73-year-old man with refractory ischemic cardiomyopathy received a HeartMate II implant as destination therapy; he presented with left chest wall swelling and tenderness. Axial unenhanced chest CT image shows a large heterogeneous high-attenuating subcutaneous fluid collection (arrow), indicative of left chest wall hematoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig22c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig23a.jpeg" height="681" width="841" aria-labelledby="fig23a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span> Spectrum of <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>-associated infections. <b>(a, b)</b> A 58-year-old man received a HeartMate II implant after left ventricular myocardial infarction; he presented with fever and tenderness and erythema around the driveline skin exit site. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(b)</b> unenhanced CT images show soft-tissue thickening and fluid accumulation surrounding the driveline and communicating with the skin (arrow), findings indicative of driveline infection. <b>(c)</b> A 64-year-old man received a HeartMate II implant as a bridge to transplant after ischemic cardiomyopathy and atrial fibrillation; he presented with fever, chills, and purulent discharge from an open anterior lower chest wall wound. Axial unenhanced chest CT image shows soft-tissue thickening and small foci of fluid and air surrounding the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> outflow bend relief and extending to the subcutaneous tissues of the lower anterior chest wall (arrow), indicative of <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> outflow graft infection. <b>(d)</b> A 39-year-old woman with refractory dilated cardiomyopathy received a HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> as a bridge to transplantation; she presented with episodes of fever and was found to have an elevated white blood cell count. Unenhanced chest CT image shows a fluid collection (arrow) surrounding the inflow cannula and <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> pump, indicative of infection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig23b.jpeg" height="681" width="834" aria-labelledby="fig23b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span> Spectrum of <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>-associated infections. <b>(a, b)</b> A 58-year-old man received a HeartMate II implant after left ventricular myocardial infarction; he presented with fever and tenderness and erythema around the driveline skin exit site. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(b)</b> unenhanced CT images show soft-tissue thickening and fluid accumulation surrounding the driveline and communicating with the skin (arrow), findings indicative of driveline infection. <b>(c)</b> A 64-year-old man received a HeartMate II implant as a bridge to transplant after ischemic cardiomyopathy and atrial fibrillation; he presented with fever, chills, and purulent discharge from an open anterior lower chest wall wound. Axial unenhanced chest CT image shows soft-tissue thickening and small foci of fluid and air surrounding the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> outflow bend relief and extending to the subcutaneous tissues of the lower anterior chest wall (arrow), indicative of <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> outflow graft infection. <b>(d)</b> A 39-year-old woman with refractory dilated cardiomyopathy received a HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> as a bridge to transplantation; she presented with episodes of fever and was found to have an elevated white blood cell count. Unenhanced chest CT image shows a fluid collection (arrow) surrounding the inflow cannula and <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> pump, indicative of infection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig23c.jpeg" height="664" width="842" aria-labelledby="fig23c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23c</span> Spectrum of <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>-associated infections. <b>(a, b)</b> A 58-year-old man received a HeartMate II implant after left ventricular myocardial infarction; he presented with fever and tenderness and erythema around the driveline skin exit site. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(b)</b> unenhanced CT images show soft-tissue thickening and fluid accumulation surrounding the driveline and communicating with the skin (arrow), findings indicative of driveline infection. <b>(c)</b> A 64-year-old man received a HeartMate II implant as a bridge to transplant after ischemic cardiomyopathy and atrial fibrillation; he presented with fever, chills, and purulent discharge from an open anterior lower chest wall wound. Axial unenhanced chest CT image shows soft-tissue thickening and small foci of fluid and air surrounding the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> outflow bend relief and extending to the subcutaneous tissues of the lower anterior chest wall (arrow), indicative of <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> outflow graft infection. <b>(d)</b> A 39-year-old woman with refractory dilated cardiomyopathy received a HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> as a bridge to transplantation; she presented with episodes of fever and was found to have an elevated white blood cell count. Unenhanced chest CT image shows a fluid collection (arrow) surrounding the inflow cannula and <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> pump, indicative of infection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig23c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig23d.jpeg" height="664" width="833" aria-labelledby="fig23d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23d</span> Spectrum of <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>-associated infections. <b>(a, b)</b> A 58-year-old man received a HeartMate II implant after left ventricular myocardial infarction; he presented with fever and tenderness and erythema around the driveline skin exit site. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(b)</b> unenhanced CT images show soft-tissue thickening and fluid accumulation surrounding the driveline and communicating with the skin (arrow), findings indicative of driveline infection. <b>(c)</b> A 64-year-old man received a HeartMate II implant as a bridge to transplant after ischemic cardiomyopathy and atrial fibrillation; he presented with fever, chills, and purulent discharge from an open anterior lower chest wall wound. Axial unenhanced chest CT image shows soft-tissue thickening and small foci of fluid and air surrounding the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> outflow bend relief and extending to the subcutaneous tissues of the lower anterior chest wall (arrow), indicative of <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> outflow graft infection. <b>(d)</b> A 39-year-old woman with refractory dilated cardiomyopathy received a HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> as a bridge to transplantation; she presented with episodes of fever and was found to have an elevated white blood cell count. Unenhanced chest CT image shows a fluid collection (arrow) surrounding the inflow cannula and <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> pump, indicative of infection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig23d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig24a.jpeg" height="750" width="739" aria-labelledby="fig24a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24a</span> Inflow cannula malposition. A 67-year-old woman with advanced sarcoidosis-related heart failure received the HeartMate II implant; she presented with recurrent low-flow alarms. Sagittal reformatted <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="volume-rendering technique">VRT</abbr> <b>(b)</b> images from <abbr title="electrocardiographic">ECG</abbr>-gated contrast-enhanced chest CT show malposition and steep angulation of the inflow cannula, which closely abuts the anterior wall of the left ventricle (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig24a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig24b.jpeg" height="750" width="736" aria-labelledby="fig24b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24b</span> Inflow cannula malposition. A 67-year-old woman with advanced sarcoidosis-related heart failure received the HeartMate II implant; she presented with recurrent low-flow alarms. Sagittal reformatted <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="volume-rendering technique">VRT</abbr> <b>(b)</b> images from <abbr title="electrocardiographic">ECG</abbr>-gated contrast-enhanced chest CT show malposition and steep angulation of the inflow cannula, which closely abuts the anterior wall of the left ventricle (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig24b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig25a.jpeg" height="874" width="710" aria-labelledby="fig25a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25a</span> Kinking of the outflow cannula. A 56-year-old woman with severe viral cardiomyopathy received the HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> implant; laboratory tests indicated hemolysis at subsequent presentation. Axial <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="volume-rendering technique">VRT</abbr> <b>(b)</b> images from <abbr title="electrocardiographic">ECG</abbr>-gated contrast-enhanced chest CT show kinking of the outflow graft (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig25a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig25b.jpeg" height="874" width="616" aria-labelledby="fig25b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25b</span> Kinking of the outflow cannula. A 56-year-old woman with severe viral cardiomyopathy received the HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> implant; laboratory tests indicated hemolysis at subsequent presentation. Axial <b>(a)</b> and <abbr title="volume-rendering technique">VRT</abbr> <b>(b)</b> images from <abbr title="electrocardiographic">ECG</abbr>-gated contrast-enhanced chest CT show kinking of the outflow graft (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig25b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig26a.jpeg" height="1087" width="673" aria-labelledby="fig26a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26a</span> Complete bend relief disconnection in a 71-year-old woman with pulmonary hypertension and severe congestive heart failure who received a HeartMate II LVAD. She presented with low-flow pump alarms and worsening symptoms of heart failure; laboratory tests indicated hemolysis. Scout <b>(a)</b>, coronal <b>(b)</b>, and VRT <b>(c)</b> images from ECG-gated contrast-enhanced CT show discontinuity of the outflow bend relief snap ring from the pump (arrow), indicative of complete bend relief disconnection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig26a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig26b.jpeg" height="507" width="651" aria-labelledby="fig26b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26b</span> Complete bend relief disconnection in a 71-year-old woman with pulmonary hypertension and severe congestive heart failure who received a HeartMate II LVAD. She presented with low-flow pump alarms and worsening symptoms of heart failure; laboratory tests indicated hemolysis. Scout <b>(a)</b>, coronal <b>(b)</b>, and VRT <b>(c)</b> images from ECG-gated contrast-enhanced CT show discontinuity of the outflow bend relief snap ring from the pump (arrow), indicative of complete bend relief disconnection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig26b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig26c.jpeg" height="507" width="652" aria-labelledby="fig26c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26c</span> Complete bend relief disconnection in a 71-year-old woman with pulmonary hypertension and severe congestive heart failure who received a HeartMate II LVAD. She presented with low-flow pump alarms and worsening symptoms of heart failure; laboratory tests indicated hemolysis. Scout <b>(a)</b>, coronal <b>(b)</b>, and VRT <b>(c)</b> images from ECG-gated contrast-enhanced CT show discontinuity of the outflow bend relief snap ring from the pump (arrow), indicative of complete bend relief disconnection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig26c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig27a.jpeg" height="798" width="663" aria-labelledby="fig27a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27a</span> Partial bend relief disconnection. A 56-year-old woman with a HeartMate II LVAD implant for treatment of severe viral cardiomyopathy presented with low pump flow. Laboratory tests indicated hemolysis. Multiplanar reformatted (left) and VRT (right) images from a contrast-enhanced ECG-gated CT examination show incomplete misalignment of the outflow bend relief snap ring (arrow) from the pump portion, consistent with partial bend relief disconnection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig27a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig27b.jpeg" height="798" width="662" aria-labelledby="fig27b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27b</span> Partial bend relief disconnection. A 56-year-old woman with a HeartMate II LVAD implant for treatment of severe viral cardiomyopathy presented with low pump flow. Laboratory tests indicated hemolysis. Multiplanar reformatted (left) and VRT (right) images from a contrast-enhanced ECG-gated CT examination show incomplete misalignment of the outflow bend relief snap ring (arrow) from the pump portion, consistent with partial bend relief disconnection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig27b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig28a.jpeg" height="803" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig28a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28a</span> Outflow graft thrombosis in a 57-year-old man with a HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> for treatment of ischemic cardiomyopathy and atrial fibrillation. The patient presented with exacerbation of heart failure symptoms, and laboratory tests indicated hemolysis. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(b)</b> images from <abbr title="electrocardiographic">ECG</abbr>-gated contrast-enhanced CT show nonopacification of the outflow graft (straight arrow) and dense opacification of the inflow cannula (curved arrow), indicative of outflow graft thrombosis. <b>(c)</b> Gross specimen after explantation of the HeartMate II device shows thrombus within the lumen of the outflow graft (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig28a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig28b.jpeg" height="803" width="739" aria-labelledby="fig28b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28b</span> Outflow graft thrombosis in a 57-year-old man with a HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> for treatment of ischemic cardiomyopathy and atrial fibrillation. The patient presented with exacerbation of heart failure symptoms, and laboratory tests indicated hemolysis. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(b)</b> images from <abbr title="electrocardiographic">ECG</abbr>-gated contrast-enhanced CT show nonopacification of the outflow graft (straight arrow) and dense opacification of the inflow cannula (curved arrow), indicative of outflow graft thrombosis. <b>(c)</b> Gross specimen after explantation of the HeartMate II device shows thrombus within the lumen of the outflow graft (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig28b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig28c.jpeg" height="647" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig28c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28c</span> Outflow graft thrombosis in a 57-year-old man with a HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> for treatment of ischemic cardiomyopathy and atrial fibrillation. The patient presented with exacerbation of heart failure symptoms, and laboratory tests indicated hemolysis. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(b)</b> images from <abbr title="electrocardiographic">ECG</abbr>-gated contrast-enhanced CT show nonopacification of the outflow graft (straight arrow) and dense opacification of the inflow cannula (curved arrow), indicative of outflow graft thrombosis. <b>(c)</b> Gross specimen after explantation of the HeartMate II device shows thrombus within the lumen of the outflow graft (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig28c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig29.jpeg" height="675" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig29" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29</span> Inflow cannula thrombosis. A 52-year-old man with ischemic cardiomyopathy underwent HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> placement; he presented with low-flow and low-volume alarms; laboratory tests indicated hemolysis. Inflow cannula thrombus was suspected on the basis of clinical and echocardiographic assessment. Photograph obtained during device explantation shows thrombus within the inflow cannula (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig29">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig30a.jpeg" height="962" width="718" aria-labelledby="fig30a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30a</span> <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>-related right ventricular failure. A 21-year-old man with drug-induced cardiomyopathy underwent placement of a HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>. Implantation of the LVAD was complicated by severe right ventricular failure, which required placement of a Thoratec paracorporeal VAD as an RVAD. <b>(a)</b> Scout image shows the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> pump (black arrow) and inflow cannula (white arrow), as well as the Thoratec PVAD–RVAD right atrium inflow cannula (black arrowhead) and pulmonary artery outflow cannula (white arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial unenhanced CT images show the <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> right atrium inflow cannula (black arrowhead) and pulmonary artery outflow cannula (arrow), as well as the aorta outflow cannula (white arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig30a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig30b.jpeg" height="962" width="607" aria-labelledby="fig30b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30b</span> <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>-related right ventricular failure. A 21-year-old man with drug-induced cardiomyopathy underwent placement of a HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr>. Implantation of the LVAD was complicated by severe right ventricular failure, which required placement of a Thoratec paracorporeal VAD as an RVAD. <b>(a)</b> Scout image shows the <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> pump (black arrow) and inflow cannula (white arrow), as well as the Thoratec PVAD–RVAD right atrium inflow cannula (black arrowhead) and pulmonary artery outflow cannula (white arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial unenhanced CT images show the <abbr title="right ventricular assist device">RVAD</abbr> right atrium inflow cannula (black arrowhead) and pulmonary artery outflow cannula (arrow), as well as the aorta outflow cannula (white arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig30b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig31a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig31a.jpeg" height="795" width="1046" aria-labelledby="fig31a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31a</span> Aortic incompetence in a 51-year-old man with progressive chest pain and dyspnea on exertion after <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> placement for ischemic cardiomyopathy. <b>(a)</b> Transthoracic Doppler echocardiogram (parasternal long-axis view) shows a large jet of regurgitant flow (white arrow) in the left ventricular outflow tract, a finding indicative of severe aortic incompetence. The patient subsequently underwent transcatheter aortic valve replacement. <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph shows the transcatheter aortic valve replacement (straight arrow) and part of the HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig31a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig31b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig31b.jpeg" height="795" width="829" aria-labelledby="fig31b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31b</span> Aortic incompetence in a 51-year-old man with progressive chest pain and dyspnea on exertion after <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> placement for ischemic cardiomyopathy. <b>(a)</b> Transthoracic Doppler echocardiogram (parasternal long-axis view) shows a large jet of regurgitant flow (white arrow) in the left ventricular outflow tract, a finding indicative of severe aortic incompetence. The patient subsequently underwent transcatheter aortic valve replacement. <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="anteroposterior">AP</abbr> chest radiograph shows the transcatheter aortic valve replacement (straight arrow) and part of the HeartMate II <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig31b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig32" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig32.jpeg" height="702" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig32" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 32</span> Partial fracture of <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> driveline in a 27-year-old woman with a HeartMate II implant for treatment of familial dilated cardiomyopathy. Oblique abdominal radiographic view obtained to investigate the cause of activated pump alarms shows fraying of the distal portion of the percutaneous driveline with separation of one of the cable wires (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig32">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig33a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig33a.jpeg" height="756" width="852" aria-labelledby="fig33a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 33a</span> Retained cannulas after <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> explantation. <b>(a)</b> A 58-year-old man underwent HeartMate II explantation for recovered myocardial function after an acute myocardial infarction attack. The inflow cannula and outflow graft were retained during explantation because of marked mediastinal and pericannular adhesions and scarring. Coronal reformatted image from contrast-enhanced CT of the chest shows the retained inflow cannula (white arrow) and outflow graft (black arrow). CT allows excellent depiction of the entire length of the retained components because of the ability to create multiplanar reconstructions. <b>(b)</b> A 27-year-old man underwent HeartMate II placement with recovering left ventricular function. The patient was deemed a high-risk candidate for <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> explantation surgery; thus, the outflow graft was percutaneously embolized (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig33a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig33b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig33b.jpeg" height="756" width="823" aria-labelledby="fig33b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 33b</span> Retained cannulas after <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> explantation. <b>(a)</b> A 58-year-old man underwent HeartMate II explantation for recovered myocardial function after an acute myocardial infarction attack. The inflow cannula and outflow graft were retained during explantation because of marked mediastinal and pericannular adhesions and scarring. Coronal reformatted image from contrast-enhanced CT of the chest shows the retained inflow cannula (white arrow) and outflow graft (black arrow). CT allows excellent depiction of the entire length of the retained components because of the ability to create multiplanar reconstructions. <b>(b)</b> A 27-year-old man underwent HeartMate II placement with recovering left ventricular function. The patient was deemed a high-risk candidate for <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> explantation surgery; thus, the outflow graft was percutaneously embolized (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig33b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig34" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig34.jpeg" height="838" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig34" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 34</span> Left ventricular pseudoaneurysm after <abbr title="left ventricular assist device">LVAD</abbr> explantation. A 32-year-old man with dilated cardiomyopathy underwent placement of a HeartMate II LVAD, later explanted because of infection. The patient presented with tachycardia and hypotension. A left-upper-quadrant pulsating mass was found at physical examination. Axial (left) and <abbr title="volume-rendering technique">VRT</abbr> (right) images from <abbr title="electrocardiographic">ECG</abbr>-gated contrast-enhanced CT reveal irregular outpouching of the left ventricular apex at the site of prior inflow cannula with a low-attenuation filling defect (arrow), indicative of a thrombosed pseudoaneurysm.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig34">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig35a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig35a.jpeg" height="567" width="782" aria-labelledby="fig35a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 35a</span> Types of <abbr title="total artificial heart">TAH</abbr> systems. <b>(a, b)</b> Photograph <b>(a)</b> and illustration <b>(b)</b> of the SynCardia <abbr title="total artificial heart">TAH</abbr> with the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> pneumatic chamber connected to the left atrial cuff and ascending aorta with two mechanical valves, and the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> pneumatic chamber connected to the right atrium and pulmonary artery with two mechanical valves. <b>(c)</b> Illustration of the AbioCor <abbr title="total artificial heart">TAH</abbr> system, which includes two artificial ventricles with their corresponding valves and a pumping system. The implantable controller and power pack are continually recharged through an energy transfer device called TETS (transcutaneous energy transmission system). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig35a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig35b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig35b.jpeg" height="567" width="402" aria-labelledby="fig35b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 35b</span> Types of <abbr title="total artificial heart">TAH</abbr> systems. <b>(a, b)</b> Photograph <b>(a)</b> and illustration <b>(b)</b> of the SynCardia <abbr title="total artificial heart">TAH</abbr> with the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> pneumatic chamber connected to the left atrial cuff and ascending aorta with two mechanical valves, and the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> pneumatic chamber connected to the right atrium and pulmonary artery with two mechanical valves. <b>(c)</b> Illustration of the AbioCor <abbr title="total artificial heart">TAH</abbr> system, which includes two artificial ventricles with their corresponding valves and a pumping system. The implantable controller and power pack are continually recharged through an energy transfer device called TETS (transcutaneous energy transmission system). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig35b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig35c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig35c.jpeg" height="565" width="664" aria-labelledby="fig35c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 35c</span> Types of <abbr title="total artificial heart">TAH</abbr> systems. <b>(a, b)</b> Photograph <b>(a)</b> and illustration <b>(b)</b> of the SynCardia <abbr title="total artificial heart">TAH</abbr> with the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> pneumatic chamber connected to the left atrial cuff and ascending aorta with two mechanical valves, and the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> pneumatic chamber connected to the right atrium and pulmonary artery with two mechanical valves. <b>(c)</b> Illustration of the AbioCor <abbr title="total artificial heart">TAH</abbr> system, which includes two artificial ventricles with their corresponding valves and a pumping system. The implantable controller and power pack are continually recharged through an energy transfer device called TETS (transcutaneous energy transmission system). (Reprinted with permission from Cleveland Clinic Center for Medical Art &amp; Photography, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig35c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig36a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig36a.jpeg" height="435" width="395" aria-labelledby="fig36a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 36a</span> Normal appearance of the SynCardia <abbr title="total artificial heart">TAH</abbr> in a 55-year-old man with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy with severe biventricular failure. Lateral chest radiograph <b>(a)</b>, axial unenhanced CT image <b>(b)</b>, and <abbr title="volume-rendering technique">VRT</abbr> image <b>(c)</b> show the <abbr title="total artificial heart">TAH</abbr> pneumatic chambers and corresponding drivelines (straight white arrow = left ventricle, straight black arrow = right ventricle pneumatic chamber). Prosthetic valves are also noted—mitral valve (white arrowhead), aortic valve (curved white arrow), tricuspid valve (black arrowhead), and pulmonary valve (curved black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig36a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig36b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig36b.jpeg" height="308" width="395" aria-labelledby="fig36b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 36b</span> Normal appearance of the SynCardia <abbr title="total artificial heart">TAH</abbr> in a 55-year-old man with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy with severe biventricular failure. Lateral chest radiograph <b>(a)</b>, axial unenhanced CT image <b>(b)</b>, and <abbr title="volume-rendering technique">VRT</abbr> image <b>(c)</b> show the <abbr title="total artificial heart">TAH</abbr> pneumatic chambers and corresponding drivelines (straight white arrow = left ventricle, straight black arrow = right ventricle pneumatic chamber). Prosthetic valves are also noted—mitral valve (white arrowhead), aortic valve (curved white arrow), tricuspid valve (black arrowhead), and pulmonary valve (curved black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig36b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig36c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig36c.jpeg" height="818" width="830" aria-labelledby="fig36c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 36c</span> Normal appearance of the SynCardia <abbr title="total artificial heart">TAH</abbr> in a 55-year-old man with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy with severe biventricular failure. Lateral chest radiograph <b>(a)</b>, axial unenhanced CT image <b>(b)</b>, and <abbr title="volume-rendering technique">VRT</abbr> image <b>(c)</b> show the <abbr title="total artificial heart">TAH</abbr> pneumatic chambers and corresponding drivelines (straight white arrow = left ventricle, straight black arrow = right ventricle pneumatic chamber). Prosthetic valves are also noted—mitral valve (white arrowhead), aortic valve (curved white arrow), tricuspid valve (black arrowhead), and pulmonary valve (curved black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig36c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig37" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.352140149/asset/images/large/rg.352140149.fig37.jpeg" height="872" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig37" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 37</span> SynCardia <abbr title="total artificial heart">TAH</abbr> infection in a 61-year-old man after <abbr title="total artificial heart">TAH</abbr> placement for refractory ischemic cardiomyopathy. The patient presented with persistent fever, and unenhanced CT was performed to assess for a source of infection. Axial (left) and multiplanar reformatted (right) images reveal a moderate fluid collection surrounding the <abbr title="total artificial heart">TAH</abbr> with a peripheral rim of thickened pericardium (straight white arrow), mediastinal stranding (curved arrow), and lymphadenopathy (black arrow). The patient was taken to the operating room for débridement and removal of the <abbr title="total artificial heart">TAH</abbr>; <i>Staphylococcus aureus</i> was isolated from mediastinal fluid cultures.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.352140149&amp;id=fig37">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Writing Committee Members, Yancy CW, et al. 2013 ACCF/AHA guideline for the management of heart failure: a report of the American College of Cardiology Foundation/American Heart Association Task Force on practice guidelines. <em>Circulation</em> 2013;128(16):e240–e327.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1161/CIR.0b013e31829e8776">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23741058/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=2013+ACCF%2FAHA+guideline+for+the+management+of+heart+failure%3A+a+report+of+the+American+College+of+Cardiology+Foundation%2FAmerican+Heart+Association+Task+Force+on+practice+guidelines&amp;author=Writing+Committee+Members&amp;author=CW+Yancy&amp;publication_year=2013&amp;journal=Circulation&amp;pages=e240-e327&amp;doi=10.1161%2FCIR.0b013e31829e8776&amp;pmid=23741058">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Senni M, Tribouilloy CM, Rodeheffer RJ, et al. Congestive heart failure in the community: trends in incidence and survival in a 10-year period. <em>Arch Intern Med</em> 1999;159(1):29–34.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1001/archinte.159.1.29">Crossref</a></d